00:02:22.120 --> 00:02:24.090
bright orange when there's
a new announcement there.

00:02:24.090 --> 00:02:28.690
So you can try clicking on it
and seeing what's in there.

00:02:28.690 --> 00:02:33.810
The next thing that we have is
sort of a detail, but many

00:02:33.810 --> 00:02:37.090
people, when they get in their
string resources, they don't

00:02:37.090 --> 00:02:39.690
know which language codes
correlate with

00:02:39.690 --> 00:02:40.750
which language name.

00:02:40.750 --> 00:02:44.540
So we're now showing the
language name and also the

00:02:44.540 --> 00:02:47.150
language code together, so that
if someone's sending you

00:02:47.150 --> 00:02:49.700
a big file, and it's specified
only by the language code, you

00:02:49.700 --> 00:02:51.660
can be completely sure that
you're putting it into the

00:02:51.660 --> 00:02:52.860
right language.

00:02:52.860 --> 00:02:55.110
So that's sort of a detail.

00:02:55.110 --> 00:02:58.705
The next thing-- probably, I
think, the most popular change

00:02:58.705 --> 00:03:01.150
is a lot of people have been
asking, how do I delete a

00:03:01.150 --> 00:03:02.690
draft application?

00:03:02.690 --> 00:03:05.550
Maybe you created an
application, oops, it was the

00:03:05.550 --> 00:03:07.000
wrong package name.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:09.640
You've switched, or you just had
some experiments that you

00:03:09.640 --> 00:03:10.650
decided not to publish.

00:03:10.650 --> 00:03:13.400
So that is now available.

00:03:13.400 --> 00:03:15.740
You can find that in the upper
right-hand corner of your

00:03:15.740 --> 00:03:19.380
Developer Console, and if you
look in the little menu where

00:03:19.380 --> 00:03:22.040
it'll say Draft, you can click
on that, and there should be

00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:25.670
an option under there that says
Delete This Application.

00:03:25.670 --> 00:03:26.930
RICH HYNDMAN: After
you've done that--

00:03:26.930 --> 00:03:27.550
ELLIE POWERS: Sorry?

00:03:27.550 --> 00:03:27.924
RICH HYNDMAN: After you've done
that, would you be able

00:03:27.924 --> 00:03:29.787
to reuse the package
name again?

00:03:29.787 --> 00:03:31.040
Is it completely gone?

00:03:31.040 --> 00:03:32.110
ELLIE POWERS: I think so.

00:03:32.110 --> 00:03:33.630
I'm not 100% sure about that.

00:03:33.630 --> 00:03:34.760
Usually, when people--

00:03:34.760 --> 00:03:36.990
I mean, there's no reason why
you would want to do that.

00:03:36.990 --> 00:03:40.990
If you have used the package
name, you should just carry on

00:03:40.990 --> 00:03:41.790
with that one.

00:03:41.790 --> 00:03:44.120
But it's more like, a lot of
people would create the wrong

00:03:44.120 --> 00:03:46.340
package name, and then realize
they need to change it.

00:03:46.340 --> 00:03:48.500
So if you already have
that package name

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:49.480
in there, it's fine.

00:03:49.480 --> 00:03:50.330
You don't have to do anything.

00:03:50.330 --> 00:03:53.750
But if you clutter up your
Developer Console, now you can

00:03:53.750 --> 00:03:54.930
declutter it.

00:03:54.930 --> 00:03:55.890
RICH HYNDMAN: From apps that
have never been published.

00:03:55.890 --> 00:03:56.170
ELLIE POWERS: Right.

00:03:56.170 --> 00:03:57.940
Once you've published an
application, even if you

00:03:57.940 --> 00:03:59.340
unpublish it, you
can't delete it.

00:03:59.340 --> 00:04:00.940
But if it's a draft, and it's
never been published,

00:04:00.940 --> 00:04:03.810
you can delete it.

