00:15:01.550 --> 00:15:05.170
So Andy has asked, "How secure
is data stored in shared

00:15:05.170 --> 00:15:07.800
preferences when using mode
private?" And he's asked, "Is

00:15:07.800 --> 00:15:10.160
it worth doing encryption?"

00:15:10.160 --> 00:15:13.720
So, mode private basically
makes the firewalls only

00:15:13.720 --> 00:15:17.350
accessible to your user
ID as an app.

00:15:17.350 --> 00:15:21.110
So if there are other apps that
are sharing your user ID,

00:15:21.110 --> 00:15:23.140
they can access those files.

00:15:23.140 --> 00:15:27.910
If the device is rooted, sort of
a rooted app could actually

00:15:27.910 --> 00:15:29.050
access those files too.

00:15:29.050 --> 00:15:30.500
So it depends on the
context of the

00:15:30.500 --> 00:15:31.930
information that you're storing.

00:15:31.930 --> 00:15:34.420
But it's sort of up
to you, really.

00:15:34.420 --> 00:15:35.520
NICK BUTCHER: And if you're
talking about encryption, then

00:15:35.520 --> 00:15:37.130
you get down to then,
where are you going

00:15:37.130 --> 00:15:38.310
to store the key?

00:15:38.310 --> 00:15:40.445
So you might just end up moving
the problem, rather

00:15:40.445 --> 00:15:42.540
than solving the problem.

00:15:42.540 --> 00:15:44.200
RICH HYNDMAN: And there's some
great guidelines published

00:15:44.200 --> 00:15:46.700
yesterday by Trevor Johns on the
Android Developers Blog,

00:15:46.700 --> 00:15:50.160
which say don't create and
store the key beforehand.

00:15:50.160 --> 00:15:52.940
Make sure you create it on the
device after run time and then

00:15:52.940 --> 00:15:55.525
store it, so that if someone
does get hold of the key, it

00:15:55.525 --> 00:15:58.040
obviously doesn't apply to every
single instance of your

00:15:58.040 --> 00:15:59.810
application.

00:15:59.810 --> 00:16:04.830
He says store the salt
for the key in local.

00:16:04.830 --> 00:16:07.005
NICK BUTCHER: And that is
relying on your user ID to

00:16:07.005 --> 00:16:07.665
protect it.

00:16:07.665 --> 00:16:08.680
RICH HYNDMAN: And then
regenerate the key

00:16:08.680 --> 00:16:09.630
when you need it.

00:16:09.630 --> 00:16:11.340
Use Secure Random.

00:16:11.340 --> 00:16:12.670
A few other things that
he's put in there.

00:16:12.670 --> 00:16:14.160
So there's a blog post that's
currently on Android

00:16:14.160 --> 00:16:16.520
Developers Blog Blogspot.

00:16:16.520 --> 00:16:18.580
NICK BUTCHER: Yeah, obviously
these are all defeated if

00:16:18.580 --> 00:16:20.120
users have rooted
their devices.

00:16:20.120 --> 00:16:22.810
So I'd say, yeah, it comes out
to if it's like your banking

00:16:22.810 --> 00:16:24.850
information or something like
that, then probably don't

00:16:24.850 --> 00:16:26.390
store it on the device.

00:16:26.390 --> 00:16:28.470
Like, anything super secure--

00:16:28.470 --> 00:16:30.915
because it's not a trusted
computing platform at the end

00:16:30.915 --> 00:16:31.910
of the day.

00:16:31.910 --> 00:16:33.727
People have access to
this information.

00:16:33.727 --> 00:16:37.140
So depends on the information.

00:16:37.140 --> 00:16:40.810
RICH HYNDMAN: What is
secure these days?

00:16:40.810 --> 00:16:42.700
